  "text": "# Prometheus TLS Configuration Audit\n\n## Summary\n\nThis audit identifies all Go source files in prometheus/prometheus that define, load, validate, and apply TLS configuration across the monitoring stack's external interfaces.\n\n## TLS Configuration Architecture\n\nPrometheus implements TLS configuration through a layered approach using two primary TLS configuration types:\n\n### 1. Configuration Definitions (config/config.go)\n\nThe main configuration file defines several structs with TLS support:\n\n- **ScrapeConfig**: Contains HTTPClientConfig (line 830) for scraping targets. TLS configuration for scrape targets is inherited from the HTTPClientConfig inline struct, which includes certificate, key, CA, and verification options.\n\n- **TracingConfig**: Directly embeds config.TLSConfig (line 1165) for OTLP trace exporters. This supports Insecure mode (line 1164) and explicit TLSConfig.\n\n- **AlertmanagerConfig**: Uses HTTPClientConfig (line 1305) for alertmanager endpoints, enabling client certificate authentication and server verification.\n\n- **RemoteWriteConfig**: Embeds HTTPClientConfig (line 1434) for remote write endpoints, with additional support for SigV4, AzureAD, and GoogleIAM authentication that work alongside TLS.\n\n- **RemoteReadConfig**: Uses HTTPClientConfig (line 1597) for remote read endpoints with the same TLS capabilities as remote write.\n\n### 2. Web Server TLS Configuration\n\n- **web/web.go**: The Handler.Run method (line 760) uses toolkit_web.ServeMultiple with a toolkit_web.FlagConfig containing the WebConfigFile path. The toolkit_web library (from github.com/prometheus/exporter-toolkit/web) handles TLS for the web server interface.\n\n- **cmd/prometheus/main.go**: The webConfig flag (line 401-403) specifies a YAML configuration file for TLS and authentication on the web server.\n\n### 3. HTTP Client Creation Chain\n\nTLS configuration flows from config.HTTPClientConfig through client instantiation:\n\n#### Scrape Targets\n- **scrape/scrape.go**: newScrapeClient function (line 2260) calls config_util.NewClientFromConfig with the ScrapeConfig.HTTPClientConfig to create HTTP clients for scraping metrics from targets.\n\n#### Remote Storage\n- **storage/remote/client.go**: NewReadClient (line 151) and NewWriteClient (line 183) functions use config_util.NewClientFromConfig to create authenticated, TLS-secured clients for remote read/write endpoints.\n- **storage/remote/storage.go**: Routes RemoteWriteConfig and RemoteReadConfig to the client creation functions, passing HTTPClientConfig.\n- **storage/remote/write.go**: Uses HTTPClientConfig from RemoteWriteConfig (line 173) when creating write clients.\n- **storage/remote/azuread/azuread.go**: Implements Azure AD authentication for remote write, working alongside HTTPClientConfig's TLS settings.\n\n#### Alertmanager Notifications\n- **notifier/alertmanagerset.go**: Creates alertmanager clients using config_util.NewClientFromConfig with HTTPClientConfig containing TLS and auth configuration.\n\n### 4. Tracing Exporter TLS Configuration\n\n- **tracing/tracing.go**: \n  - ApplyConfig method (line 71-105) checks TLS configuration changes (line 75-76) to determine if tracer provider reload is needed.\n  - buildTracerProvider function (line 131) orchestrates tracer creation.\n  - getClient function (line 179) applies TLS configuration for both gRPC (line 189) and HTTP (line 222) OTLP clients using config_util.NewTLSConfig.\n\n### 5. Service Discovery Endpoints\n\nAll 33 service discovery plugins support TLS through HTTPClientConfig for their API endpoints:\n\n**AWS Plugins** (6 files):\n- discovery/aws/aws.go, ec2.go, ecs.go, elasticache.go, lightsail.go, msk.go\n\n**Azure/Kubernetes**:\n- discovery/azure/azure.go, discovery/kubernetes/kubernetes.go\n\n**Container Orchestration**:\n- discovery/moby/docker.go, dockerswarm.go\n- discovery/nomad/nomad.go\n- discovery/marathon/marathon.go\n\n**Cloud Providers**:\n- discovery/consul/consul.go, discovery/digitalocean/digitalocean.go, discovery/eureka/eureka.go\n- discovery/hetzner/hcloud.go, hetzner.go, robot.go\n- discovery/http/http.go\n- discovery/ionos/ionos.go, server.go\n- discovery/linode/linode.go\n- discovery/openstack/openstack.go\n- discovery/puppetdb/puppetdb.go\n- discovery/scaleway/baremetal.go, instance.go, scaleway.go\n- discovery/stackit/server.go, stackit.go\n- discovery/uyuni/uyuni.go\n- discovery/vultr/vultr.go\n\n**Service Mesh & API Gateways**:\n- discovery/xds/client.go, kuma.go, xds.go\n\nEach SD plugin defines an HTTPClientConfig field in its configuration struct and uses config_util.NewClientFromConfig or config.NewClientFromConfig to instantiate TLS-secured HTTP clients for discovering targets or service metadata.\n\n## TLS Enforcement Points\n\n1. **Client Certificate Validation**: HTTPClientConfig supports CA certificate paths, client certificates/keys, and insecure skip verify flags.\n\n2. **Server Verification**: CA certificate validation for remote endpoints is configurable per endpoint (scrape targets, remote storage, alertmanagers, SD endpoints).\n\n3. **Web Server**: Configurable through exporter-toolkit's web package with certificate/key configuration via --web.config.file flag.\n\n4. **Tracing**: Explicit TLS support for gRPC and HTTP OTLP exporters with configurable CA and client certificates.\n\n5. **Service Discovery**: Each plugin independently validates TLS for its respective API endpoint.\n\n## Dependencies\n\nThe actual TLS configuration implementation relies on:\n- **github.com/prometheus/common/config**: Provides HTTPClientConfig and TLSConfig types, and NewClientFromConfig/NewTLSConfig functions\n- **github.com/prometheus/exporter-toolkit/web**: Handles web server TLS via toolkit_web.ServeMultiple\n- **crypto/tls**: Standard Go TLS library used by the common package\n\n## Validation Locations\n\nTLS configuration validation occurs at:\n- HTTPClientConfig.Validate() calls in config/config.go (lines 858, 1340, 1473, 1628)\n- TracingConfig.UnmarshalYAML validation (lines 1177-1199)\n- toolkit_web.Validate() in cmd/prometheus/main.go (line 1145)"
